WHAT DID YOU DO DURING THE WAR, DADDY?<br><br>
Dear Doc Spatz<br><br>
You say that Communism is dead, and yet I've read the same things you have posted here in your defense and in hopes of substantiating what you believe  30 years ago. Do you known where I read those same words, doc? On the leaflets dropped along jungle trails in the Republic of South Vietnam. <br>
Talk about being had. <br>
When we &quot;Warriors,&quot; returned it was hard for us to believe that &quot;Americans,&quot; at home believed what those leaflets said. It was pure Communist propaganda and you were had, then and continue to believe them today. <br><br>
You take credit for being a loyal American and stopping the war.<br>
Funny thing I heard Daniel Ortega say the same words to the people of Nicaragua just before he revealed his Communist agenda. Wake up Doc. <br>
The only thing you accomplished was get more Americans killed. <br>
History is beginning to reveal that individuals like yourself actually prolonged the war and were instrumental in killing more South Vietnamese civilians through your condemnation of our intervention in South Vietnam then all the soldiers that accidentally or intentionally did kill civilians.<br><br>
Hanoi looked at your protest as encouragement for them to fight on, to continue to wage their war of terror and destruction against the South Vietnamese population and they had a field day with your support.<br><br>
You also cannot divorce yourself from the Jane Fonda Communist connection any more then the labels you have learned for what you did during the war. <br>
What did you do during the war Daddy?<br>
Face it doc, you have twisted your individual selfish actions into self-righteousness and have been hiding there all these years. <br>
You refer to JFK stating he probably saw the trap that Nam was, and got his head blown off for wanting to stop it. <br>
Hogwash, visit your compatriots Tom Dier's web site, or better yet I've pasted a portion of President Kennedy's answer to a Letter From South Vietnamese President Ngo Dinh Diem requesting American involvement here. However, you may read both letters in thread #49 Factual Database Info Center.  Read also the sample of the leaflets dropped in South Vietnam by the Communist North Vietnam soldiers and tell me if they don't sound like you and your compatriots as the commies called you.<br><br>
Portion of Kennedy's call to arms.<br><br>
December 14, 1961 <br><br>
Dear Mr. President (Diem): <br><br>
I have received your recent letter in which you described so cogently the dangerous condition caused by North Vietnam's efforts to take over your country. The situation in your embattled country is well known to me and to the American people. We have been deeply disturbed by the assault on your country. Our indignation has mounted as the deliberate savagery of the Communist program of assassination, kidnapping, and wanton violence became clear. <br><br>
Your letter underlines what our own information has convincingly shown - that the campaign of force and terror now being waged against your people and your government is supported and directed from the outside by the authorities at Hanoi. They have thus violated the provisions of the Geneva Accords designed to ensure peace in Vietnam and to which they are bound themselves in 1954. <br><br>
In accordance with that declaration, and in response to your request, we are prepared to help the Republic of Vietnam to protect its people and to preserve its independence. We shall promptly increase our assistance to your defense effort as well as help relieve the destruction of the floods which you describe. I have already given the orders to get those programs underway. <br><br>
The United States, like the Republic of Vietnam, remains devoted to the cause of peace and our primary purpose is to help your people maintain their independence. If the Communist authorities in North Vietnam will stop their campaign to destroy the Republic of Vietnam, the measures we are taking to assist your defense efforts will no longer be necessary. <br><br>
John F. Kennedy<br><br>
Doc you call yourself a loyal Americans who finally won the war by stopping it.<br>
But doc it was individuals like you that caused veterans the most pain and sorrow then what they saw in the fields of battle.  <br>
We saw you and still do in the same light as Hanoi Hanna, Jane Fonda and all draft dodgers that fled to Canada. <br>
You carried the banner of protecting young men from going to war. Doc I will gladly send you a copy of the leaflets that said the same things you have posted here written 30 years ago by the Liberation Army, printed in Hanoi by the Communist. Did you write it for them? They called themselves the Liberation Army; here in American we call it active socialism.<br>
 It's the same thing, pure Communism and its not dead doc. <br>
It only took two steps backwards this time instead of its customary two steps forward and one step backwards. Visit China and read the condemnation of the people rights to practice religious freedom in China today, it's in the Los Angeles Times, in today's edition and then tell me that Communism is dead. Visit your children's schools and read their textbooks and the Communist liberal agenda that is there and very much alive and real and supported by individuals like yourself. <br><br>
Doc you're right, it is you that must live with your actions for the rest of your life. <br>
While I was in Vietnam, I realized that I had made a difference.  Marines are alive today that would not be if I had not volunteered for duty, If I had not believed in my country and in what we were doing there. <br>
Many American fighting men volunteered for duty because they believed in American in our way of life and the price that must be paid for that freedom. Today their names are etched on that black reflective wall in Washington, D.C. <br><br>
But you know what doc, why do you visit this site so often, you were not here from its inception? I ask you why? <br>
It just might be that deep hidden quilt residing in the deepest crevices of your heart. You knew what was right but choose instead to hide and have been involved in hiding that shame ever since. <br>
Next time you get a chance doc visit the wall and get up close to it, you might hear the cries of those that paid the ultimate price crying out and asking you why? <br>
Why, why didn't you support Communism?<br>
 Why did you choose to believe a lie?<br><br>
In War and Peace,<br>
I'm Cook Barela and those are my thoughts, <br><br>

